Milton perhaps, but Mil- ton alone, excells him, in his picture of the loves of our first parents, in the garden of Eden. The purity of this painting is indeed only equalled by its elegance.

So spake our general mother, and with eyes Of conjugal attraction unreprov'd, And meek surrender, half-embracing lean'd On our first father: half her swelling breast Naked met his, under the flowing gold Of her loose tresses hid.
